WEBVTT

00:05.339 --> 00:08.467
<i>[intense music]</i>

00:08.467 --> 00:14.556
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.556 --> 00:17.309
<i>- My name is Tony Miller.</i>
<i>I'm 51-years old.</i>

00:17.309 --> 00:19.144
I'm a retired Navy officer.

00:19.144 --> 00:21.605
<i>My family is definitely</i>
<i>rooting for me back home.</i>

00:21.605 --> 00:26.109
I've been married for...

00:26.109 --> 00:28.320
let me think.

00:28.320 --> 00:30.697
I'm sorry, Dina.
[laughs]

00:30.697 --> 00:33.116
<i>- My name is Rebel Rodriguez.</i>
<i>I'm 19-years old.</i>

00:33.116 --> 00:34.576
I originally was taught

00:34.576 --> 00:36.703
in a more traditional
Japanese style.

00:36.703 --> 00:38.830
<i>So I've only</i>
<i>really started to learn</i>

00:38.830 --> 00:41.917
<i>oil quenching recently</i>
<i>due to Japanese blades</i>

00:41.917 --> 00:44.294
mostly being
quenched in water.

00:44.294 --> 00:47.381
<i>- I'm Chuck Cook.</i>
<i>I'm from Dundee, Oregon.</i>

00:47.381 --> 00:51.927
My shop is pretty low-key.
I have no power hammers,

00:51.927 --> 00:53.762
<i>no hydraulic presses,</i>

00:53.762 --> 00:56.306
but I'm pretty excited about
using the ones here.

00:56.306 --> 00:59.768
<i>- My name's Steve Lewis.</i>
<i>I'm 35-years old.</i>

00:59.768 --> 01:03.480
My strategy to win this
is to stay calm and focused.

01:03.480 --> 01:06.358
<i>I'm not someone</i>
<i>who runs around real crazy.</i>

01:06.358 --> 01:08.485
<i>It's a calm storm.</i>

01:08.485 --> 01:11.655
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:11.655 --> 01:13.782
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:13.782 --> 01:15.659
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:15.659 --> 01:17.953
specifically designed
to explore

01:17.953 --> 01:20.539
and push the boundaries
of weaponsmithing.

01:20.539 --> 01:22.708
Whether or not you guys
rise to that occasion

01:22.708 --> 01:25.877
remains to be seen
by our panel of expert judges.

01:25.877 --> 01:27.796
These are the men who decide
which of you will be

01:27.796 --> 01:29.631
our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:29.631 --> 01:31.842
and leave here
with a check for $10,000.

01:31.842 --> 01:32.884
Let's meet them now.

01:32.884 --> 01:36.054
ABS Mastersmith, J. Nielson.

01:36.054 --> 01:39.808
Historic Weapons Re-creation
Specialist, David Baker.

01:39.808 --> 01:43.395
Edged-weapons Specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:43.395 --> 01:45.355
Bladesmiths,
one of the things I find

01:45.355 --> 01:47.107
most fascinating
about you guys,

01:47.107 --> 01:48.734
is you guys
look around your world

01:48.734 --> 01:51.486
and anything metal
becomes a blade in your mind.

01:51.486 --> 01:53.447
Today, you'll be using these.

01:53.447 --> 01:58.577
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:58.577 --> 02:00.829
- [laughs]

02:01.955 --> 02:04.458
- Bicycles in a stand?

02:04.458 --> 02:06.543
Did they hide
hardenable tool steel

02:06.543 --> 02:07.919
<i>in the frame or something?</i>

02:07.919 --> 02:09.421
- Today's first challenge,

02:09.421 --> 02:11.798
you'll have to combine
two or more steels

02:11.798 --> 02:14.134
in order to make
a Damascus billet

02:14.134 --> 02:15.802
from which
to forge your blades.

02:15.802 --> 02:18.555
- We have to use
two different pieces of steel

02:18.555 --> 02:21.099
off these bikes,
so I'm already thinking

02:21.099 --> 02:22.893
<i>canister Damascus.</i>

02:22.893 --> 02:25.312
- All right, blade--oh,
one more thing, bladesmiths.

02:25.312 --> 02:27.731
We've removed
all of the canisters

02:27.731 --> 02:29.608
from The Forge today.

02:29.608 --> 02:31.151
- [chuckles]

02:31.151 --> 02:33.487
- So if you plan on doing
a canister Damascus,

02:33.487 --> 02:36.031
<i>you'll have to find</i>
<i>a creative workaround.</i>

02:36.031 --> 02:37.491
- There's no canisters.

02:37.491 --> 02:39.785
That really ups
the difficulty level.

02:39.785 --> 02:41.578
- Keep in mind
that in the second round

02:41.578 --> 02:44.039
you'll be attaching handles
to those Damascus blades

02:44.039 --> 02:45.707
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

02:45.707 --> 02:48.043
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:48.043 --> 02:49.795
in a bike frame chop

02:49.795 --> 02:52.130
and for edge retention
in an inner tube slice.

02:52.130 --> 02:55.092
You will have three hours
in which to finish your work.

02:55.092 --> 02:57.302
Your time starts...
now.

02:57.302 --> 03:00.389
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:00.389 --> 03:02.057
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:02.057 --> 03:05.852
How much of the material
is usable to make Damascus, J.?

03:05.852 --> 03:09.356
- As far as hardenable steel,
probably maybe around 15%.

03:09.356 --> 03:12.609
First thing I'd be going for
is the bike chain.

03:12.609 --> 03:14.778
- Knives from old bicycles.

03:14.778 --> 03:17.531
<i>The only thing I can think of</i>
<i>that's hardenable on that</i>

03:17.531 --> 03:19.533
is bicycle chain.

03:19.533 --> 03:21.243
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:21.243 --> 03:23.120
<i>Just trying</i>
<i>to run through my mind,</i>

03:23.120 --> 03:26.081
"What are the other pieces
that could be even used here?"

03:26.081 --> 03:29.042
- Well, he cut
a piece of chain off first.

03:29.042 --> 03:31.878
- And he cut some sprocket
off there, as well.

03:31.878 --> 03:34.214
<i>- I already know there's</i>
<i>nothing on a bicycle</i>

03:34.214 --> 03:36.091
big enough
to make these knives from

03:36.091 --> 03:38.218
without doing
a canister Damascus,

03:38.218 --> 03:42.097
<i>but I don't know</i>
<i>where to get a canister from.</i>

03:42.097 --> 03:44.433
Then I realize that

03:44.433 --> 03:48.603
we have to harvest pieces
from the rack itself

03:48.603 --> 03:50.021
<i>to make a canister.</i>

03:50.021 --> 03:51.773
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:51.773 --> 03:54.359
<i>Chuck and I</i>
<i>work together at getting</i>

03:54.359 --> 03:58.238
one long piece cut off
to make each of our canisters.

03:58.238 --> 03:59.698
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:59.698 --> 04:01.241
Yep.

04:01.241 --> 04:02.409
- There you go.

04:02.409 --> 04:04.578
- Smart move.

04:04.578 --> 04:06.830
- Do you think
cainster Damascus is gonna be

04:06.830 --> 04:08.290
the theme of this challenge?

04:08.290 --> 04:09.875
- Oh, yeah.
- I think so.

04:09.875 --> 04:11.501
- Would you rather use
the one on the bike frame

04:11.501 --> 04:13.879
or on the bike rack?
- I'd rather use the rack.

04:13.879 --> 04:17.340
Do you use the bike frame?
Which you could do.

04:17.340 --> 04:19.342
You'd make, like,
several small cans

04:19.342 --> 04:21.720
then have to layer them up
and forge weld those.

04:21.720 --> 04:23.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:23.472 --> 04:25.307
<i>- I have to make</i>
<i>canister Damascus</i>

04:25.307 --> 04:27.392
because the pieces
of the steel

04:27.392 --> 04:29.060
<i>are just so small.</i>

04:29.060 --> 04:30.812
- Rebel's got
a section of chain.

04:30.812 --> 04:32.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:32.564 --> 04:35.817
<i>- I'm also thinking</i>
<i>the gear-like piece</i>

04:35.817 --> 04:37.736
where the pedals attached.

04:37.736 --> 04:39.529
- You never know
what these things are made of

04:39.529 --> 04:41.364
or the quality of the steel
that you have in there.

04:41.364 --> 04:44.284
So start doing
your spark testing.

04:44.284 --> 04:47.037
- When I test it out,
I find it's not gonna work.

04:47.037 --> 04:48.747
It's just--there's
not enough carbon in it.

04:48.747 --> 04:50.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:50.081 --> 04:51.708
<i>The gear on the rear wheel</i>

04:51.708 --> 04:53.126
<i>should be</i>
<i>a pretty hard piece of steel.</i>

04:53.126 --> 04:54.669
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:54.669 --> 04:56.671
I spark tested this piece
and it seems to be

04:56.671 --> 04:59.424
somewhat
of a hardenable steel.

04:59.424 --> 05:02.969
<i>- There's not a lot of</i>
<i>useable steel on the bicycle.</i>

05:02.969 --> 05:05.972
I'm thinking bike chain,
but we have to have a second,

05:05.972 --> 05:07.265
so what's the second?

05:07.265 --> 05:09.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:09.768 --> 05:12.103
- He's cutting the springs
out of the back of the seat.

05:12.103 --> 05:13.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:13.897 --> 05:15.816
- Oh, that's a good idea.
- Didn't even think of that.

05:15.816 --> 05:18.568
5160 coil springs
in the back of the seat.

05:18.568 --> 05:20.320
- At this point
I'm feeling pretty good.

05:20.320 --> 05:22.489
<i>Feel like</i>
<i>I have time on my side.</i>

05:22.489 --> 05:24.241
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:24.241 --> 05:26.660
- My plan of attack
is to go for the bearings

05:26.660 --> 05:28.119
and the chain.

05:28.119 --> 05:29.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:29.704 --> 05:31.373
- Let's find out
if he's got bearings in there.

05:31.373 --> 05:33.667
Which he does.
- Are those hardenable?

05:33.667 --> 05:36.002
- Well, bearings are hardenable
but they're covered in grease

05:36.002 --> 05:38.171
and I hope Steve
cleans them off first.

05:38.171 --> 05:41.508
<i>- My next step now is to use</i>
<i>a little bit of 1095 powder,</i>

05:41.508 --> 05:43.343
<i>weld it up, get it hot,</i>

05:43.343 --> 05:44.970
<i>and then peel</i>
<i>the canister off of this</i>

05:44.970 --> 05:46.555
and see where my billet's at.

05:46.555 --> 05:49.850
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:49.850 --> 05:51.768
- Oh.
- Ooh, ha.

05:51.768 --> 05:53.061
- Rebel's having
a little trouble

05:53.061 --> 05:55.021
with that cut-off wheel.

05:55.021 --> 05:57.732
- I've never used
an angle grinder.

05:57.732 --> 05:59.943
Picking one up was
a little interesting.

05:59.943 --> 06:02.571
- Rebel finally cut his piece
of canister from the frame.

06:02.571 --> 06:05.073
That took about twice as long
as everybody else.

06:05.073 --> 06:07.117
- I plan on
keeping the canister on.

06:07.117 --> 06:08.994
<i>All I have to do</i>
<i>is make sure there's</i>

06:08.994 --> 06:10.579
<i>no canister left on the edge</i>

06:10.579 --> 06:12.789
so there is
no soft steel on the edge.

06:12.789 --> 06:15.041
<i>That will give me more time</i>
<i>to work on my blade</i>

06:15.041 --> 06:18.545
<i>and really get it finished up</i>
<i>and looking pretty.</i>

06:18.545 --> 06:21.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:21.298 --> 06:25.176
- So Tony actually
is using the liquid paper.

06:25.176 --> 06:28.263
Why is that the thing that
you line your canister with?

06:28.263 --> 06:30.473
- That's what actually
prevents the canister

06:30.473 --> 06:33.518
from adhering to the materials
you use on the inside

06:33.518 --> 06:35.395
and the hardenable stuff.

06:35.395 --> 06:37.731
<i>- The liquid paper's</i>
<i>running out the bottom.</i>

06:37.731 --> 06:42.235
I should stop and go back
to weld that hole up

06:42.235 --> 06:44.529
<i>but I'm</i>
<i>trying to be optimistic</i>

06:44.529 --> 06:47.032
<i>thinking it's not as big</i>
<i>as it really is.</i>

06:47.032 --> 06:50.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:50.744 --> 06:53.371
- Tony's forge looks like
the Fourth of July over there.

06:53.371 --> 06:55.498
- Tony's welds
aren't complete on both sides

06:55.498 --> 06:57.042
so he's losing
some powder there.

06:57.042 --> 06:58.710
- Whoa.
Backing up.

06:58.710 --> 07:00.587
all: Whoa, whoa.

07:00.587 --> 07:02.088
- Whoa.
- Uh...

07:02.088 --> 07:03.798
- That would not be
a good weld there.

07:03.798 --> 07:05.759
- That's not a birthday candle;
that's a road flare.

07:05.759 --> 07:08.553
- My poor MIG welding
comes back to bite me.

07:08.553 --> 07:10.597
and I just have no idea
what to do with it now.

07:10.597 --> 07:12.140
- What I would have
tried to do

07:12.140 --> 07:14.267
is not let
all that material spill

07:14.267 --> 07:17.270
and go re-weld
those caps real quick.

07:17.270 --> 07:18.855
I think Tony's gonna
start over.

07:18.855 --> 07:23.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:23.360 --> 07:26.029
<i>- So I should be using</i>
<i>liquid paper</i>

07:26.029 --> 07:28.281
to keep the can
from welding on

07:28.281 --> 07:30.533
or causing me problems
down the road,

07:30.533 --> 07:32.827
but I'm making
the choice not to

07:32.827 --> 07:36.665
because I don't have time
for the liquid paper to dry.

07:36.665 --> 07:39.292
- Honestly, by eliminating
the whiteout step

07:39.292 --> 07:41.211
in a rushed situation
like this,

07:41.211 --> 07:43.213
you're eliminating the need
to take the can off.

07:43.213 --> 07:44.547
So it's a really good idea.

07:44.547 --> 07:51.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:51.304 --> 07:53.223
Steve's doing really good.
- Yeah.

07:53.223 --> 07:55.684
- He's got one end of
his canister welded up.

07:55.684 --> 07:57.185
He's feeding chain into it.

07:57.185 --> 07:58.895
So he's got
a lot of material in there.

07:58.895 --> 08:01.606
- Was starting to use
the bearings...

08:01.606 --> 08:05.568
realized that there's
grease on them...

08:05.568 --> 08:06.945
and didn't clean them.

08:06.945 --> 08:08.321
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:08.321 --> 08:10.407
Grease is
not gonna be something

08:10.407 --> 08:12.534
that's gonna work well
inside of this canister.

08:12.534 --> 08:14.703
<i>The metals won't bind.</i>

08:14.703 --> 08:16.538
Can I use the front part
of your bike?

08:16.538 --> 08:18.540
- Yeah, go ahead.
- Okay.

08:18.540 --> 08:22.919
So I aborted that,
and now I'm going for the axle.

08:22.919 --> 08:25.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:25.213 --> 08:26.631
Rushing.
I need to slow down

08:26.631 --> 08:28.800
a little bit.

08:28.800 --> 08:30.593
<i>I change my plan</i>

08:30.593 --> 08:33.012
and I'm praying
to the knife gods

08:33.012 --> 08:34.764
that it's gonna work out.

08:34.764 --> 08:36.933
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:36.933 --> 08:39.185
- Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed.

08:39.185 --> 08:42.939
You have two hours remaining
to finish your work.

08:42.939 --> 08:45.108
- I'm thinking to myself,
this is a disaster.

08:45.108 --> 08:47.902
I've already wasted
at least an hour of my time

08:47.902 --> 08:49.904
and now I have to start over.

08:49.904 --> 08:52.365
And then
a thought occurs to me.

08:52.365 --> 08:54.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:54.325 --> 08:57.328
I can cut
the end of this off...

08:57.328 --> 09:01.958
refill all the powdered steel,
and weld a new end on it.

09:01.958 --> 09:04.210
- Didn't Tony already have
the smallest canister

09:04.210 --> 09:05.587
out there already?
- Yeah.

09:05.587 --> 09:08.423
- Ooh.
Well, it just got shorter.

09:08.423 --> 09:10.008
- Hopefully he can pull
enough material out

09:10.008 --> 09:11.634
to meet the parameters.

09:11.634 --> 09:14.888
I go back to my old nemesis,
the MIG welder.

09:14.888 --> 09:17.348
This time, I'm not going
to leave any gaps

09:17.348 --> 09:19.100
in this weld,
no matter what it takes.

09:19.100 --> 09:22.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:22.312 --> 09:23.772
This heat's tearing me up.

09:23.772 --> 09:27.859
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:27.859 --> 09:30.028
<i>- Everything seems to be</i>
<i>going well as I'm pressing it.</i>

09:30.028 --> 09:32.113
Everything seems to be
pretty soft in there.

09:32.113 --> 09:33.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:33.990 --> 09:37.619
And I start
to cut off my canister.

09:37.619 --> 09:42.290
What I want to see is a nice,
solid piece of steel in there.

09:42.290 --> 09:43.583
- Let's see what happens.

09:43.583 --> 09:45.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:45.794 --> 09:47.337
- [bleep].

09:47.337 --> 09:48.797
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:48.797 --> 09:51.132
My billet inside is cracked.

09:51.132 --> 09:53.093
<i>It's something</i>
<i>I can't keep going with.</i>

09:53.093 --> 09:54.511
- His billet squeezed
tight enough

09:54.511 --> 09:55.845
and not enough heat

09:55.845 --> 09:58.056
and everything
just fractured inside.

09:58.056 --> 09:59.516
- Steve's starting over.

09:59.516 --> 10:00.975
- Is he gonna have
enough time to finish

10:00.975 --> 10:02.811
if he starts over?
- I don't think so.

10:02.811 --> 10:07.357
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:07.357 --> 10:10.777
- I'm sweating profusely.
I'm starting to feel shaky.

10:13.363 --> 10:14.948
Come here to this chair.

10:14.948 --> 10:16.866
<i>- I've been working</i>
<i>at a feverish pace</i>

10:16.866 --> 10:19.035
to try to recover
from that mistake

10:19.035 --> 10:22.372
and get caught up,
but I've overdone it.

10:22.372 --> 10:24.541
<i>My blood pressure</i>
<i>is very high.</i>

10:24.541 --> 10:26.292
- Man,
this is not good for Tony.

10:26.292 --> 10:27.669
Not looking good at all.

10:29.212 --> 10:31.923
- No.
No, no, no, no, no, no.

10:31.923 --> 10:33.415
We might have
our first double elimination.

10:37.220 --> 10:39.139
<i>- I've been working</i>
<i>at a feverish pace,</i>

10:39.139 --> 10:40.348
<i>but I've overdone it.</i>

10:40.348 --> 10:42.142
- Man,
this is not good for Tony.

10:42.142 --> 10:43.726
Not looking good at all.

10:45.061 --> 10:47.313
- No.
No, no, no, no, no, no.

10:47.313 --> 10:49.983
- I can't--sir.
I--

10:49.983 --> 10:52.443
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

10:52.443 --> 10:54.612
- Can I sit for a few minutes
and take it again?

10:54.612 --> 10:56.406
- Yeah, I'll give you
five minutes.

10:56.406 --> 10:59.284
- For medical reasons,
he might not be coming back.

10:59.284 --> 11:03.997
- Trying everything possible
to will my blood pressure down.

11:03.997 --> 11:06.875
- Tony's steel
is still in the fire.

11:06.875 --> 11:08.293
- That billet of steel

11:08.293 --> 11:11.004
has been heated so much
for so long

11:11.004 --> 11:14.424
his grain structure's gotta be
immense in there.

11:14.424 --> 11:18.678
- You're now down to 160/80
if you're gonna go.

11:18.678 --> 11:22.223
You wanna do this?
- I'm gonna try it.

11:22.223 --> 11:24.142
[all cheer]

11:24.142 --> 11:26.019
- There we go.
- Let's do this.

11:26.019 --> 11:28.730
- Nice.
[clapping]

11:28.730 --> 11:31.274
I will turn in a knife,
no matter what it takes.

11:31.274 --> 11:32.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:32.775 --> 11:35.445
- Now he's
even ahead of Steve.

11:35.445 --> 11:36.821
Wow.

11:36.821 --> 11:38.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:38.406 --> 11:39.866
<i>- I see Tony</i>
<i>come back on the floor,</i>

11:39.866 --> 11:41.284
<i>which is a good thing.</i>

11:41.284 --> 11:43.244
I don't want to see
anybody get hurt,

11:43.244 --> 11:47.415
but I had to start over,
so it's not looking so good.

11:47.415 --> 11:49.167
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:49.167 --> 11:51.085
<i>- Now that I've been</i>
<i>to the press three times,</i>

11:51.085 --> 11:53.421
<i>the next move is</i>
<i>to go to big blue</i>

11:53.421 --> 11:56.216
<i>and start drawing</i>
<i>the billet out.</i>

11:56.216 --> 11:57.717
Behind you.

11:57.717 --> 11:59.594
<i>I've never used</i>
<i>an air hammer before.</i>

11:59.594 --> 12:01.429
I'm pretty nervous.

12:01.429 --> 12:05.183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:05.183 --> 12:07.101
<i>That's one</i>
<i>of the greatest pieces</i>

12:07.101 --> 12:09.771
of equipment ever.
It just--it feels right.

12:09.771 --> 12:11.856
- For somebody who
doesn't have power tools

12:11.856 --> 12:13.274
at his own shop,

12:13.274 --> 12:14.817
he's cruising along
like it's nothing.

12:14.817 --> 12:17.278
- It's going pretty good.
It seems solid.

12:17.278 --> 12:18.821
I didn't remove the can,

12:18.821 --> 12:20.615
so I'm hoping
that doesn't hurt me later.

12:20.615 --> 12:22.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:22.242 --> 12:25.119
- I'm actually not
looking forward to the moment

12:25.119 --> 12:26.496
the can is ready
to be welded

12:26.496 --> 12:28.706
because that is
the moment of truth.

12:28.706 --> 12:32.418
<i>If it's a bad first weld,</i>
<i>you're set up for disaster.</i>

12:32.418 --> 12:34.128
- Hopefully
he got that hot enough.

12:34.128 --> 12:38.132
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:38.132 --> 12:40.260
- It feels solid.
There's no...

12:40.260 --> 12:42.011
<i>squishy, un-welded parts.</i>

12:42.011 --> 12:44.264
I actually pulled through
on the welds.

12:44.264 --> 12:47.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:47.558 --> 12:50.436
- Steve needs to make
quick work of this shaping.

12:50.436 --> 12:51.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:51.854 --> 12:53.815
Because Tony's
charging back strong.

12:53.815 --> 12:55.650
- This may not be
a pretty blade,

12:55.650 --> 12:58.653
<i>but it is going to be</i>
<i>a finished blade</i>

12:58.653 --> 13:03.157
<i>before that clock</i>
<i>ticks down to zero.</i>

13:03.157 --> 13:06.911
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:06.911 --> 13:08.705
- Nobody can touch
Chuck right now.

13:08.705 --> 13:11.416
Chuck is in the zone.

13:11.416 --> 13:13.376
<i>- All I need to do</i>
<i>at this point</i>

13:13.376 --> 13:15.878
is just get
all the heat treating done.

13:15.878 --> 13:21.926
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:21.926 --> 13:25.847
- Chuck's gotta file.
- Seems pretty solid.

13:25.847 --> 13:28.224
So I'm feeling
pretty confident.

13:28.224 --> 13:30.977
I just have some canister
to grind off.

13:30.977 --> 13:34.105
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:34.105 --> 13:35.940
- Looks like Rebel
ground a little bit of a curve

13:35.940 --> 13:37.442
into that blade.

13:37.442 --> 13:38.943
It's got a bit of
a trailing point on it now.

13:38.943 --> 13:41.237
- Yep.
<i>- The clock is ticking.</i>

13:41.237 --> 13:43.114
If I mess up the quench
and have to redo it,

13:43.114 --> 13:44.949
<i>it's gonna be</i>
<i>a very close call.</i>

13:44.949 --> 13:46.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:46.701 --> 13:48.286
- And there you go.
Rebel's in the quench.

13:48.286 --> 13:49.454
- Nice.

13:49.454 --> 13:52.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:52.498 --> 13:54.208
- I feel pretty good
about this blade.

13:54.208 --> 13:55.710
I'm actually really amazed.

13:55.710 --> 13:58.838
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:58.838 --> 14:00.757
- Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

14:00.757 --> 14:02.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:02.341 --> 14:04.177
- Did Tony just quench?
- I think he did.

14:04.177 --> 14:06.804
- Yep.
Tony quenched.

14:06.804 --> 14:09.307
- Comeback Tony.

14:09.307 --> 14:10.683
- I gotta get a quench on this.

14:10.683 --> 14:11.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:11.934 --> 14:13.561
- Go quench, buddy.

14:13.561 --> 14:15.396
It's time.

14:15.396 --> 14:17.982
- 50 seconds left on the clock.
He's back in The Forge.

14:17.982 --> 14:20.735
- Will he get it up to
temperature when he quenches?

14:20.735 --> 14:22.445
- No.
I don't think so.

14:22.445 --> 14:25.698
- Ten, nine, eight,

14:25.698 --> 14:28.910
seven, six, five,

14:28.910 --> 14:30.828
four, three--
- Leave it in the oil.

14:30.828 --> 14:33.331
- Two, one...

14:33.331 --> 14:35.458
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

14:35.458 --> 14:37.794
This round is over.

14:37.794 --> 14:39.837
<i>- I made a lot of</i>
<i>mistakes this round,</i>

14:39.837 --> 14:41.464
<i>but I did</i>
<i>the best that I could.</i>

14:41.464 --> 14:43.633
Hopefully everything
will work out.

14:43.633 --> 14:46.677
- Bladesmiths, in this
first round of competition,

14:46.677 --> 14:50.556
we challenged you to make
a signature Damascus blade.

14:50.556 --> 14:53.059
Now, it's time to see
if you rose to the occasion.

14:53.059 --> 14:55.311
- Tony, please present
your work to the judges.

14:55.311 --> 14:56.938
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:56.938 --> 14:58.940
<i>- There's still a lot of work</i>
<i>to be done here,</i>

14:58.940 --> 15:00.358
but things look
pretty well aligned.

15:00.358 --> 15:02.360
My big concern is

15:02.360 --> 15:04.237
the grain structure
of this steel,

15:04.237 --> 15:06.906
'cause there were times that
your steel stayed in the forge

15:06.906 --> 15:08.533
and it got pretty hot.

15:08.533 --> 15:10.201
This might be
extremely brittle.

15:10.201 --> 15:12.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:12.537 --> 15:13.996
- Rebel.
You're up.

15:13.996 --> 15:16.707
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:16.707 --> 15:18.334
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:18.334 --> 15:20.086
<i>- First up, it was fun</i>
<i>to watch you out there.</i>

15:20.086 --> 15:21.796
<i>You have patience, my friend.</i>

15:21.796 --> 15:23.714
What I like about it
is the shape.

15:23.714 --> 15:25.258
It's very reminiscent of

15:25.258 --> 15:27.510
some southeast Asian machetes
I've seen.

15:27.510 --> 15:30.471
So it's gonna work well
for slashing and chopping.

15:30.471 --> 15:32.390
Good job.

15:32.390 --> 15:33.808
- Chuck, you're up.

15:33.808 --> 15:35.601
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:35.601 --> 15:37.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:37.145 --> 15:39.605
<i>- Bit of a kink here</i>
<i>in your tang.</i>

15:39.605 --> 15:41.774
Your tang and blade
are slightly out of alignment,

15:41.774 --> 15:43.651
but that's a pretty easy fix.

15:43.651 --> 15:45.611
Otherwise, nicely done.

15:47.196 --> 15:48.614
- Steve, you're up.

15:48.614 --> 15:50.324
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:50.324 --> 15:51.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:51.701 --> 15:53.953
- Well, I like seeing
a good comeback.

15:53.953 --> 15:55.580
You did a great job
shifting gears.

15:55.580 --> 15:57.123
- Thank you.
- But I'll tell ya...

15:57.123 --> 15:59.500
you're killing me
with this one-minute quench.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.836
- Yeah.
- 30 minutes in...

16:01.836 --> 16:03.629
You can quench this thing
and then shape it

16:03.629 --> 16:05.006
and deal with
any of these issues

16:05.006 --> 16:06.883
like the warp
and things like that.

16:06.883 --> 16:08.509
Biggest concern is that quench.

16:08.509 --> 16:10.219
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:10.219 --> 16:13.222
- Bladesmiths, you've heard
the judges' critiques.

16:13.222 --> 16:16.434
Now, it's time for them
to go into deliberation.

16:16.434 --> 16:18.019
Please place your blades
on this table

16:18.019 --> 16:19.353
and step off The Forge floor.

16:19.353 --> 16:26.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:30.323 --> 16:31.699
Okay, judges.

16:31.699 --> 16:33.326
We've done preliminary looks.

16:33.326 --> 16:35.077
Now, let's get
into the details.

16:35.077 --> 16:37.038
We'll start
with Tony's blade.

16:37.038 --> 16:39.207
<i>- Tony's has got</i>
<i>so much going on here.</i>

16:39.207 --> 16:42.001
I mean, it's so unrefined,
I don't know where it's going.

16:42.001 --> 16:43.711
This is a rush job.

16:43.711 --> 16:45.588
- Well, why don't we check
the hardness on that edge.

16:45.588 --> 16:48.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:48.883 --> 16:50.760
- It's softer right here.
- Mm-hmm.

16:50.760 --> 16:52.094
- And harder on the front half.

16:52.094 --> 16:53.679
- But the blade
has been hardened?

16:53.679 --> 16:55.139
- But the blade
does have hardness in it.

16:55.139 --> 16:57.016
- All right, let's move on
to our next bladesmith

16:57.016 --> 16:58.643
and that's Rebel.

16:58.643 --> 17:00.895
<i>- Rebel got creative.</i>
<i>I kind of like that.</i>

17:00.895 --> 17:02.813
<i>We're not doing</i>
<i>a stabbing test</i>

17:02.813 --> 17:05.316
<i>so don't need to have</i>
<i>the point right in the front.</i>

17:05.316 --> 17:07.151
These concern me though.

17:07.151 --> 17:09.111
These notches up here.

17:09.111 --> 17:11.864
He really needs to taper down
this spine to get rid of those

17:11.864 --> 17:13.658
'cause that can be
stress fractures

17:13.658 --> 17:14.909
just waiting to blow apart.

17:14.909 --> 17:17.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:17.078 --> 17:19.163
Not perfect hardness,
but it is hard.

17:19.163 --> 17:21.457
- All right, so let's move on
to our next bladesmith,

17:21.457 --> 17:24.001
and that's Chuck.

17:24.001 --> 17:25.836
<i>- Chuck's made</i>
<i>some great steel here.</i>

17:25.836 --> 17:28.214
<i>I mean, you can see</i>
<i>that pattern in there already.</i>

17:28.214 --> 17:29.966
<i>There's a little bit</i>
<i>of a warp in the blade.</i>

17:29.966 --> 17:33.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:33.052 --> 17:35.221
- That's a nice, hard blade.

17:35.221 --> 17:37.598
- All right,
our last bladesmith is Steve.

17:37.598 --> 17:39.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:39.892 --> 17:41.686
<i>Steve definitely has</i>
<i>some warping.</i>

17:41.686 --> 17:43.479
<i>He basically has an S.</i>

17:43.479 --> 17:46.983
But the real concern is
his heat treat, so let's see.

17:46.983 --> 17:48.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:48.776 --> 17:50.403
[all sigh]

17:50.403 --> 17:53.155
That's not good.
Ah, that's not good at all.

17:53.155 --> 17:57.326
So it's not properly hardened.
- Okay.

17:57.326 --> 17:58.828
Final decision?
- Yes, I have.

17:58.828 --> 18:00.246
- Dave, you've made yours?
- Oh, yeah.

18:00.246 --> 18:01.747
- J.?
- Oh, yeah.

18:01.747 --> 18:03.124
- Let's go tell our smiths.

18:03.124 --> 18:04.875
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:04.875 --> 18:06.627
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

18:06.627 --> 18:08.337
It's time
for one of you smiths

18:08.337 --> 18:10.298
to leave The Forge.

18:10.298 --> 18:12.466
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge is...

18:12.466 --> 18:16.470
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:16.470 --> 18:19.473
Steve.
Your blade didn't make the cut.

18:19.473 --> 18:20.850
J. Nielson's gonna
tell you why.

18:20.850 --> 18:22.310
- Now, Steve,
I gotta commend you.

18:22.310 --> 18:24.103
You had a problem
with that first canister,

18:24.103 --> 18:26.272
you dropped it,
and made a whole new one.

18:26.272 --> 18:28.274
Finished a blade
to present to us.

18:28.274 --> 18:30.318
But when we took a file to it,
it was soft,

18:30.318 --> 18:31.861
and that's why
we have to let you go.

18:31.861 --> 18:33.237
- I understand.
Thank you.

18:33.237 --> 18:35.406
- Steve,
please surrender your blade.

18:35.406 --> 18:37.450
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:37.450 --> 18:41.621
- I rushed the quench,
and that's a rookie mistake.

18:41.621 --> 18:44.165
<i>Even though</i>
<i>I went home first...</i>

18:44.165 --> 18:46.125
I was able to present a knife

18:46.125 --> 18:48.961
<i>and I'm glad I was able</i>
<i>to turn something in.</i>

18:48.961 --> 18:51.130
- Bladesmiths,
congratulations.

18:51.130 --> 18:54.258
Your work has earned you a spot
in the second round.

18:54.258 --> 18:55.968
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:55.968 --> 18:58.262
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

18:58.262 --> 18:59.847
by attaching handles
to your blades.

18:59.847 --> 19:01.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:01.557 --> 19:03.517
At the end of this round,
your weapons will be tested

19:03.517 --> 19:05.019
for strength and durability

19:05.019 --> 19:07.355
in a bicycle frame chop

19:07.355 --> 19:11.359
and for edge retention
in an inner tube slice.

19:11.359 --> 19:13.778
Bladesmiths, you have two hours
in this round.

19:13.778 --> 19:16.614
Good luck.
Your time starts...now.

19:16.614 --> 19:19.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:19.367 --> 19:21.327
- I like it when they jump.
- These guys, they do

19:21.327 --> 19:23.454
hustle around pretty well.
- They do.

19:23.454 --> 19:25.831
- I need to get that
blade edge in water

19:25.831 --> 19:27.625
<i>and heat the spine of that up</i>

19:27.625 --> 19:29.335
<i>to soften the back</i>
<i>of that spine</i>

19:29.335 --> 19:31.837
<i>and mitigate</i>
<i>any grain growth problems</i>

19:31.837 --> 19:33.464
that may have occurred.

19:33.464 --> 19:35.216
<i>Right now,</i>
<i>it's very brittle</i>

19:35.216 --> 19:37.176
<i>and susceptible to breaking</i>

19:37.176 --> 19:39.679
<i>when he chops</i>
<i>that bicycle frame.</i>

19:39.679 --> 19:41.305
- If you soften it,
glue back it,

19:41.305 --> 19:42.932
you're actually
taking the brittleness,

19:42.932 --> 19:44.475
the hardness out.

19:44.475 --> 19:46.811
<i>- This is not a fast process,</i>

19:46.811 --> 19:49.021
but trying to do things
too fast

19:49.021 --> 19:51.399
is what got me in this trouble
in the first place.

19:51.399 --> 19:56.070
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:56.070 --> 19:57.988
- What I'll be doing
in round two

19:57.988 --> 20:01.033
is building a three-layered
frame design handle.

20:01.033 --> 20:04.036
<i>What I like about this handle</i>
<i>is you don't have to deal with</i>

20:04.036 --> 20:06.455
<i>having to forge a full tang</i>
<i>in the first round.</i>

20:06.455 --> 20:08.791
However, I will have to take
a little more time

20:08.791 --> 20:10.459
on this round
building that frame,

20:10.459 --> 20:12.086
<i>but it pays off in the end.</i>

20:12.086 --> 20:14.338
- Normally when you're
doing a frame handle,

20:14.338 --> 20:17.675
<i>you're using metal</i>
<i>for the frame</i>

20:17.675 --> 20:20.720
to make a through tang knife
look like a full tang knife,

20:20.720 --> 20:23.139
but having surfaces
glued together

20:23.139 --> 20:26.100
you're just asking for handles
to fracture and come apart.

20:28.102 --> 20:30.271
<i>I can see there's gonna</i>
<i>be a lot of work ahead.</i>

20:30.271 --> 20:33.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:33.941 --> 20:35.818
- Let's take a look over here
at Chuck.

20:35.818 --> 20:38.404
He had probably
the most finished blade

20:38.404 --> 20:39.947
coming out of round one.

20:39.947 --> 20:41.907
- I choosed a brown micarta

20:41.907 --> 20:43.743
because it's big and fat

20:43.743 --> 20:45.995
and so that way I can try
and leave the bottom belled

20:45.995 --> 20:47.997
so that it helps prevent
the handle

20:47.997 --> 20:50.374
<i>from coming out of their hand</i>
<i>as they chop.</i>

20:50.374 --> 20:52.084
At this point,
I'm feeling pretty good.

20:52.084 --> 20:54.462
I feel like
I have time on my side,

20:54.462 --> 20:56.505
but it's gonna go
pretty quick.

20:56.505 --> 20:58.174
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:58.174 --> 21:01.427
- Bladesmiths,
you have 90 minutes remaining

21:01.427 --> 21:02.928
to finish your blades.

21:02.928 --> 21:04.680
- I'm way behind.

21:04.680 --> 21:05.973
I've gotta
get this handle done.

21:05.973 --> 21:07.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:07.808 --> 21:11.562
I chose a micarta which is
a strong synthetic material.

21:11.562 --> 21:13.689
- Tony used the corby bolts.

21:13.689 --> 21:15.608
How are they different
than the pins, J.?

21:15.608 --> 21:17.026
- Pins can break free.

21:17.026 --> 21:18.611
There's nothing actually
holding them in

21:18.611 --> 21:20.404
unless you peen them over.

21:20.404 --> 21:23.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:23.699 --> 21:25.451
<i>- I am sort of struggling with</i>

21:25.451 --> 21:29.038
the fact that this handle
has a lot of moving parts.

21:29.038 --> 21:31.248
<i>Every second counts,</i>
<i>and I have to get</i>

21:31.248 --> 21:33.959
a lot of pieces
to come together very quickly.

21:33.959 --> 21:37.046
<i>If I mess up the glue up,</i>
<i>I have to start over</i>

21:37.046 --> 21:38.547
and I don't have
enough time for that.

21:38.547 --> 21:39.757
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:39.757 --> 21:40.883
- Moment of truth.

21:40.883 --> 21:42.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:48.220 --> 21:49.475
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:49.475 --> 21:51.685
<i>- The pins aren't even all</i>
<i>the way through on one side.</i>

21:51.685 --> 21:54.355
- Oh, that's bad.

21:54.355 --> 21:56.106
- Hopefully there are
no gaps in that at all.

21:56.106 --> 21:58.150
- There's some big gaps
in the front.

21:58.150 --> 21:59.777
- He looks confused.

21:59.777 --> 22:01.737
- Yeah, he looks like he's
trying to figure it out.

22:01.737 --> 22:04.323
- I think it's time
to just throw in extra glue

22:04.323 --> 22:06.492
<i>'cause I just don't</i>
<i>have time to fix that.</i>

22:06.492 --> 22:08.869
- There's so much glue
pouring out of every hole

22:08.869 --> 22:10.371
on that thing,
it's hard for me to tell

22:10.371 --> 22:12.456
if there's actually pins
in the holes.

22:12.456 --> 22:15.042
- I'm feeling a little worried
because I just want this handle

22:15.042 --> 22:16.293
to come out functional.

22:16.293 --> 22:19.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:19.713 --> 22:21.507
- Chuck was critiqued
on his tang

22:21.507 --> 22:22.925
and he's not doing anything.

22:22.925 --> 22:25.344
He's just slapping
some scales on it.

22:25.344 --> 22:27.179
<i>- I choose not</i>
<i>to address the tang</i>

22:27.179 --> 22:29.390
because I need to turn in
a finished blade

22:29.390 --> 22:32.184
with a handle
that meets all the parameters.

22:32.184 --> 22:34.019
<i>Hopefully this doesn't</i>
<i>send me home.</i>

22:34.019 --> 22:37.147
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:37.147 --> 22:38.858
- One hour has elapsed!

22:38.858 --> 22:41.527
You have just 60 minutes
remaining to finish your work.

22:41.527 --> 22:44.613
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.613 --> 22:46.824
<i>- Still not as far along</i>
<i>as I would like to be.</i>

22:46.824 --> 22:49.952
I had turned my attention
to sharpening my blade.

22:49.952 --> 22:52.079
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:52.079 --> 22:53.372
- You got
some weird sci-fi noises

22:53.372 --> 22:54.999
coming from over there.

22:54.999 --> 22:56.917
- I've never heard those noises
here in The Forge.

22:56.917 --> 22:58.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.711 --> 23:01.422
- It's the weird contours
of Tony's knife

23:01.422 --> 23:04.425
producing the
ultra-sonic vibrations.

23:07.261 --> 23:11.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:11.599 --> 23:13.017
<i>- I need to take care</i>
<i>of some notches</i>

23:13.017 --> 23:14.310
<i>in the back of my knife,</i>

